<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="495" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,295,1221]" pageId="5" pageNumber="495">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,225,295,320]" pageId="5" pageNumber="495">Hosts.</emphasis>
Oligophagous on hosts belonging to 19 genera in 
<taxonomicName box="[809,901,296,319]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="5" pageNumber="495" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Poaceae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Garcia" box="[917,1231,295,320]" pageId="5" pageNumber="495" refString="Garcia Morales, M., Denno, B., Miller, D. R., Miller, G. L., Ben-Dov, Y. &amp; Hardy, N. B. (2016) ScaleNet: A Literature-based model of scale insect biology and systematics. Available from: http: // scalenet. info (accessed 31 May 2016)" type="journal article" year="2016">
García Morales 
<emphasis box="[1104,1163,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="495">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Lastra" pageId="5" pageNumber="495" refString="Lastra, L. A. &amp; Gomez, L. A. (1997) Observaciones del ciclo de vida de la escama blanca Duplachionaspis divergens (Green) (Homoptera: Diaspididae) y reconocimiento de enemigos naturales. In: Congreso de la Asociacion Colombiana de Tecnicos de la Cana de Azucar, Tecnicana. 4 Memorias. Cali, Colombia. pp. 41 - 52." type="journal article" year="1997">Lastra &amp; Gómez 1997</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="495" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,295,1221]" pageId="5" pageNumber="495">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,367,392]" pageId="5" pageNumber="495">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Adult female cover flat, white, broadly oyster-shell shaped; exuviae marginal, yellow to brown. Slide-mounted characters of adult female: with 2 pairs of well-developed lobes; median lobes divergent, not yoked basally, with a pair of distinct marginal setae between them. Gland spine formula: 2-2-2(3). Macroducts on pygidium subequal in size, without ducts between medial lobes; submedial ducts present on segments 3 to 6. Dorsal microducts present on submedial and submarginal areas of segments 1 to 3. Perivulvar pores present in 5 groups, with approximately 45 pores on each side of body. Anterior spiracles each with 10–12 pores, posterior spiracles with 5–10 pores (
<bibRefCitation author="Yu" box="[451,631,583,608]" pageId="5" pageNumber="495" refString="Yu, H. M. &amp; Suh, S. J. (2013) A New record for the genus Duplachionaspis armored scale (Hemiptera: Diaspididae) from Korea. Korean Journal of Applied Entomology, 52 (1), 63 - 67." type="journal article" year="2013">Yu &amp; Suh 2013</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="495" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,295,1221]" pageId="5" pageNumber="495">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,620,645]" pageId="5" pageNumber="495">Distribution.</emphasis>
Australasian, Nearctic, Neotropical, Oriental and Palaearctic regions (
<bibRefCitation author="Garcia" pageId="5" pageNumber="495" refString="Garcia Morales, M., Denno, B., Miller, D. R., Miller, G. L., Ben-Dov, Y. &amp; Hardy, N. B. (2016) ScaleNet: A Literature-based model of scale insect biology and systematics. Available from: http: // scalenet. info (accessed 31 May 2016)" type="journal article" year="2016">
García Morales 
<emphasis box="[1375,1436,620,645]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="495">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry box="[262,375,655,680]" name="Colombia" pageId="5" pageNumber="495">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, this species was recorded for the first time in the department of 
<collectingRegion box="[1114,1292,655,680]" country="Colombia" name="Valle del Cauca" pageId="5" pageNumber="495">Valle del Cauca</collectingRegion>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Lastra" pageId="5" pageNumber="495" refString="Lastra, L. A. &amp; Gomez, L. A. (1997) Observaciones del ciclo de vida de la escama blanca Duplachionaspis divergens (Green) (Homoptera: Diaspididae) y reconocimiento de enemigos naturales. In: Congreso de la Asociacion Colombiana de Tecnicos de la Cana de Azucar, Tecnicana. 4 Memorias. Cali, Colombia. pp. 41 - 52." type="journal article" year="1997">Lastra &amp; Gómez (1997)</bibRefCitation>
. We record it from 
<collectingRegion box="[533,639,692,717]" country="Colombia" name="Risaralda" pageId="5" pageNumber="495">Risaralda</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[693,751,693,716]" country="Colombia" name="Meta" pageId="5" pageNumber="495">Meta</collectingRegion>
departments.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,295,1221]" pageId="5" pageNumber="495">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,471,727,752]" pageId="5" pageNumber="495">Economic importance.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[480,787,727,752]" class="Insecta" family="Diaspididae" genus="Duplachionaspis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="495" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="divergens">
<emphasis box="[480,787,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="495">Duplachionaspis divergens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been reported as a 
<taxonomicName box="[1062,1129,727,752]" class="Insecta" family="Diaspididae" genus="Serenaspis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="495" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minor">minor</taxonomicName>
pest of sugarcane in 
<collectingCountry box="[1378,1436,727,752]" name="India" pageId="5" pageNumber="495">India</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[201,311,764,789]" name="Colombia" pageId="5" pageNumber="495">Colombia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Lastra" box="[328,592,764,788]" pageId="5" pageNumber="495" refString="Lastra, L. A. &amp; Gomez, L. A. (1997) Observaciones del ciclo de vida de la escama blanca Duplachionaspis divergens (Green) (Homoptera: Diaspididae) y reconocimiento de enemigos naturales. In: Congreso de la Asociacion Colombiana de Tecnicos de la Cana de Azucar, Tecnicana. 4 Memorias. Cali, Colombia. pp. 41 - 52." type="journal article" year="1997">Lastra &amp; Gómez 1997</bibRefCitation>
). It is a commonly encountered, grass-infesting armored scale in 
<collectingRegion box="[1348,1432,764,789]" country="United States of America" name="Florida" pageId="5" pageNumber="495">Florida</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[151,207,800,824]" name="United States of America" pageId="5" pageNumber="495">USA</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Evans" box="[225,497,799,824]" pageId="5" pageNumber="495" refString="Evans, G. A. &amp; Hodges, G. S. (2007) Duplachionaspis divergens (Hemiptera: Diaspididae) A new exotic pest of sugarcane and other grasses in Florida. Florida Entomologist, 90 (2), 392 - 393." type="journal article" year="2007">Evans &amp; Hodges 2007</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry box="[553,666,799,824]" name="Colombia" pageId="5" pageNumber="495">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, although it was recorded in the sugarcane growing region of the department of 
<collectingRegion box="[324,512,836,861]" country="Colombia" name="Valle del Cauca" pageId="5" pageNumber="495">Valle del Cauca</collectingRegion>
, populations are generally low and no control is required (
<bibRefCitation author="Uribe" box="[1213,1424,836,861]" pageId="5" pageNumber="495" refString="Uribe, J. J., Cuellar, J. &amp; Gomez, L. A. (1997) Manejo comercial de la escama blanca de la cana de azucar, Duplachionaspis divergens (Homoptera: Diaspididae), en el Ingenio Risaralda. In: Memorias del IF Congreso Colombiano de la Asociacion de Tecnicos de la Cana de Azucar (Tecnicana), Tomo 1, pp. 52 - 60." type="journal article" year="1997">
Uribe 
<emphasis box="[1291,1345,836,861]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="495">et al</emphasis>
. 1997
</bibRefCitation>
). However, 
<bibRefCitation author="Bustillo" box="[267,437,871,896]" pageId="5" pageNumber="495" refString="Bustillo, A. (2013) Insectos plaga y organismos beneficos del cultivo de la cana de azucar en Colombia. Centro de Investigacion de la Cana de Azucar de Colombia Cenicana, Cali, 157 pp." type="book" year="2013">Bustillo (2013)</bibRefCitation>
reported that a foliar infestation of up to 30% (presence of scales on one third of the leaf area) can cause losses to sugarcane production and the damage is worst in places where the soil has low fertility.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
